CPLN 590 Midterm Project â€“ Predicting Home Sale Prices in San Francisco

Natasha Tabachnikoff & Eugene Chong

October 20, 2019

Introduction

What is the purpose of this project?

The purpose of this project is to predict the sale price of homes sold in San Francisco between 2012 and 2015 using what we know about other homes sold in the city during the same time period. By relating various characteristics of homes, such as their square footage or neighborhood, to their sale prices, we develop a model that predicts the sale prices of homes with similar characteristics.

Why should we care about it?

For cities, is it important for tax assessment purposes to have accurate information about the market value of homes to capture rising property values and fund necessary public services. For consumers, having publicly available market value estimates on sites like Zillow helps to correct informational imbalances that negatively impact homebuyers and sellers with less information and social capital.

What makes this a difficult exercise?

The housing market is notoriously heterogeneous, meaning that there is a huge diversity of â€œproductsâ€ on the market serving many different needs, wants, and capacities. Preferences fluctuate with wider demographic, cultural, and economic trends, and many markets and consumer groups overlap. Further, housing generally appreciates in value over decades and centuries, distinguishing it from consumer goods that are also much less complex. These many different traits, both internal to the structure of a home and determined by its neighborhood, all demand different prices on the market. Hedonic modeling weights all these different features and assesses their value in the aggregate based on comparable properties in the market.

What is your overall modeling strategy?

San Francisco has a severe housing supply crisis and has (some of) the highest housing costs in the country. To onlookers, the cityâ€™s housing market can look irrational, and the relatively low volume of sales interactions obfuscates the nuances of what homebuyers value. This project tries to predict home prices by quantifying the relationship between characteristics of homes (like physical structure, neighborhood desirability, spatial organization, and access to amenities) with the known sale prices of those homes. The first step was collecting data: we gathered and cleaned data from publicly available sources that we believed would predict the sale price of a home. We then used those data to create a multiple linear regression model to determine the relationship between those home characteristics and home sale price. Lastly, we refined and finalized our model through the process of cross-validation. We split our dataset of home sale prices into training sets and test sets, using the training sets to teach our model and using the test sets to check the quality of our predictions. We added and removed predictor variables from our model until we found the one that produced the most accurate and consistent predictions for home sale prices in San Francisco.

Briefly summarize your results.

Our model, based on 12 variables, was able to predict home prices with an average percent error of about 20%, with some errors for higher priced homes being much larger. These dramatic overpredictions of higher cost homes impacted the overall accuracy of our model, bringing our average absolute error to about $220,000. Our model showed minimal spatial bias â€“ the spatial distribution of our prediction errors had a Moranâ€™s I of 0.041. Our model did show some demographic bias, predicting home sale values more accurately in low income (MAPE = 19.1%) and majority non-white (16.6%) neighborhoods compared to in high income (21.5%) and majority white (23.9%) neighborhoods. The rest of this report will dive into the data we explored, our process for selecting and refining variables, the distribution of errors in our predictions, and a discussion of the generalizability of this model.

Data

Data Collection

We collected and cleaned data that we believed would predict the sale price of a home. Our final model included the variables below, though we examined many others while building and refining the model.

  • Internal Characteristics: The sales data included some characteristics describing the home. Our final model included the following variables.
    • Property Area â€“ Square footage of the home (only includes built area, not the whole lot)
    • Number of Rooms
    • Age of Home â€“ Calculated based on the YearBuilt and Sale Year variables
    • Sale Year
    • Sale Month
  • Amenities: We used the robust catalogue on DataSF to map proximity to public features and amenities, like parks, commercial areas, and high-performing schools. Being insulated from disamenities like crime and intensive industrial land uses is also important to homebuyers, so we spent time quantifying and refining those features.
    • Crimes â€“ Number of assaults, burglaries, and vehicle thefts that occurred within 1/8 of a mile of each property
    • Tree Cover â€“ Binary variable indicating whether there were street trees located within 20 feet of the property
    • Distance from industrial zoning â€“ Industrial zones tend to be high noise and pollution areas, disamenities for homes
  • Demographics: San Francisco is a historically unequal city, and homebuyers still attach stigmas to many of its neighborhoods. Because of continuing racial and socioeconomic segregation by those with the most resources, the greatest wealth (and highest home prices) are still clustered. We collected demographic data on income and race from the Census and ACS to see which parts of the city were the most exclusive.
    • White Percentage
    • Average Annual Household Income
  • Spatial Structure: Because home sale prices tend to cluster across space, the prices of nearby homes can help predict the sale price of a particular property.
    • Neighborhood â€“ Categorical variable for the propertyâ€™s neighborhood
    • Spatial Lag â€“ Average sale price of the 20 nearest property sales

Methods

To make our predictions for sale price, we created a multiple linear regression model. After constructing our features for each home sale, we split the data into a training set (60%) and a test set (40%). We used the training set to teach the model a relationship between the various explanatory variables we analyzed and the homeâ€™s sale price. We removed factors with no or minimal predictive power and further refined other features to be better predictors. We then used this model to predict the prices on the test set, and we evaluated our model based on how well it predicted the sale prices for the test set. We used k-folds cross-validation to test our modelâ€™s consistency â€“ by repeating the training set/test set split 100 times, we could see how reliably our model produced predictions with a certain level of accuracy.

Dealing with Missing Data

Some of our data were incomplete. We did not include variables that were missing a significant percentage of their observations, such as the number of bedrooms. For variables missing a smaller percentage of their observations, such as property area, we imputed values using the neighborhood average.

Imputing values for variables is an important step in the process. Linear regression models can only be trained on observations with information for every explanatory variable. Our model includes 12 explanatory variables, each of which has some number of missing values. Since our sample is about 9,500 home sales, we could simply remove the incomplete observations and still have a large enough sample size to train the model. Doing so, however, may introduce a systematic bias into our model, since observations with NA values for a variable may share a common characteristic that is relevant to sale price. Removing those observations from our data set would mean our model is not trained to recognize the relevance of those characteristics to sale price.

Test Set Prediction Results

The table below shows some statistics assessing the quality of our predictions on the test set.

  • MAE: On average, our predictions were off by about $220,000. Note that the average home in our dataset sold for $1.14 million.
  • MAPE: On average, our predictions were off by about 20%.
  • R-Squared: Our model accounted for 68% of the variation in the sale price in the test set.
MAE <- st_set_geometry(sales.test_predict, NULL) %>%
  summarize(mean(SalePrice.AbsError, na.rm = T)) %>%
  pull()

MAPE <- st_set_geometry(sales.test_predict, NULL) %>%
  summarize(mean(SalePrice.APE, na.rm = T) * 100) %>%
  round(2)
  
R2 <- cor(sales.test_predict$SalePrice, sales.test_predict$SalePrice.Predict, method = "pearson") ^ 2

Cross-Validation Results

Our cross-validation results show evaluation statistics after transforming our predicted log sale price values back into regular sale prices. The model has some issues with consistency. The standard deviation of Mean Average Percent Error (MAPE) across the 100 folds, for instance, is nearly 1/3 of the average MAPE.

resamples <- data.frame(table(lapply(reg.cv$control$indexOut, length))) %>% 
  dplyr::select(-Freq) %>% 
       gather(Fold, Obs) %>% 
  mutate(Obs = as.numeric(Obs))

folds <- vector()

for (blah in resamples$Fold) {
  
  bloop <- rep(blah, times = resamples %>% filter(Fold == blah) %>% pull(Obs))  
  folds <- c(folds, bloop)
    
}

CV_results <- data.frame(Fold = folds,
      log_SalePrice = reg.cv$finalModel$model$.outcome,
      SalePrice = exp(reg.cv$finalModel$model$.outcome),
      log_SalePrice.Predict = reg.cv$finalModel$fitted.values,
      SalePrice.Predict = exp(reg.cv$finalModel$fitted.values)) %>% 
  mutate(AE = abs(SalePrice.Predict - SalePrice),
         APE = abs(SalePrice.Predict - SalePrice) / SalePrice) %>% 
  group_by(Fold) %>% 
  dplyr::summarize(MAE = mean(AE),
            MAPE = mean(APE),
            R2 = cor(SalePrice.Predict, SalePrice) ^ 2)

CV_kable <- data.frame(Mean_MAE = mean(CV_results$MAE),
                       SD_MAE = sd(CV_results$MAE),
                       Mean_MAPE = round(mean(CV_results$MAPE), 2) * 100,
                       SD_MAPE = round(sd(CV_results$MAPE), 2) * 100,
                       Mean_R2 = round(mean(CV_results$R2), 2),
                       SD_R2 = round(sd(CV_results$R2), 2))

kable(CV_kable, 
      col.names = c("Average MAE", "Std Deviation of MAE", "Average MAPE",
                    "Std Deviation of MAPE", "Average R-Squared", "Std Deviation of R-Squared"),
      caption = "100-fold Cross-Validation Results") %>% 
  kable_styling(full_width = F)

Plot of Prediction results

Our model included several very high overpredictions, including one prediction of nearly $12,000,000. These overpredictions have an outsized effect on our evaluation metrics and our goodness-of-fit line below (the green line). Refining our model with features that limit the number of these overpredictions would likely significantly improve the predictive power of our model.

sales.predict_all <-
  final_sales_all %>%
  # need to exponentiate since we predicted log sale price
  mutate(SalePrice.Predict = predict(training_reg, final_sales_all, na.action=na.pass) %>% exp(), 
         SalePrice.Error = SalePrice - SalePrice.Predict,
         SalePrice.AbsError = abs(SalePrice - SalePrice.Predict),
         SalePrice.APE = (abs(SalePrice - SalePrice.Predict)) / SalePrice)

Our calculated Moranâ€™s I of 0.041 shows that our test set residuals are very slightly clustered. The p-value of 0.001 shows that this small amount of clustering is greater than would be expected through random chance alone.

coords.test <- sales.test_predict %>%
  st_coordinates()

neighborList.test <- knn2nb(knearneigh(coords.test, 5))

spatialWeights.test <- nb2listw(neighborList.test, style="W")

sales.test_predict$lagPriceError <- lag.listw(spatialWeights.test, sales.test_predict$SalePrice.Error)

moranTest <- moran.mc(sales.test_predict$SalePrice.Error, 
                      spatialWeights.test , nsim = 999)

ggplot(as.data.frame(moranTest$res[c(1:999)]), aes(moranTest$res[c(1:999)])) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 0.01) +
  geom_vline(aes(xintercept = moranTest$statistic), colour = "#FA7800",size=1) +

Is your model generalizable?

Our model is not perfectly generalizable. It is more accurate at assessing home sale prices in low income and majority non-white neighborhoods. Why is this a concern? If this model (or one similar) was used to assess homes for property tax purposes, it could overcharge wealthier neighborhoods for public services. This is definitely preferable to the alternative: the long-standing discriminatory practice of placing a higher tax burden on minorities through inflated assessments in lower income, majority-minority neighborhoods. However, this makes the model non-generalizable and would probably lead to some angry wealthy homeowners.

Discussion

Is this an effective model?

As demonstrated in the plots and maps above, our model is extremely good at predicting home sale prices around $1 million dollars. However, it slightly underpredicted home prices below that, and overpredicted (sometimes dramatically) home prices above that. Because there any many homes selling in San Francisco for significantly over $1 million, our modelâ€™s lower predictive power in the upper quartiles makes it less effective.

What were some of the more interesting variables? Describe the more important predictor variables.

Sale year and month were surprisingly predictive. This was because of the focus years of our study: 2012-2015. As the housing market in San Francisco has grown from competitive to astronomically exclusive, prices have steadily increased to reflect the constrained supply.

Our most predictive variables were actually quite foreseeable. Size, median household income of the census tract a home was in, and susceptibility to crime were some of the most predictive factors.

How much of the variation in prices could you predict? Describe the error in your predictions. The average difference between our home sale price prediction and the actual price was about 220,000 dollars. Our variables account for well over half of the variation in home prices, with our average R-squared at .68. However, these averages donâ€™t tell the complete story, as our errors varied widely. The standard deviation of our predictions was about $ 120,000 (this is visualized by the Distribution of MAE plot).

According to your maps, could you account for the spatial variation in prices? Where did the model predict particularly well? Poorly? Why do you think this might be?

While the map of sale price shows that higher price homes are clearly clustered in particular neighborhoods, the map of our sale price prediction errors did not show similar clustering. This is quantified by the Moranâ€™s I test of the errors which shows a Moranâ€™s I of slightly above 0, indicating that our model accounted for much of the spatial variation in prices.

Conclusion

Would you recommend your model to Zillow? Why or why not? How might you improve this model?

Zillow publishes limited assessments of its Zestimate accuracy. In their latest report from June of 2019, their predictions for off-market homes in San Francisco err only 7.2% from the actual price, making their Zestimates within 10% of the sale price in 62.4% of transactions. This is much more accurate than our predictions with a MAPE around 20%. We donâ€™t know where Zillowâ€™s predictions have the largest errors (homes selling for lower or higher prices), so we canâ€™t say if Zestimates have the issue as we did with predicting the home sales in the upper quartile.

One thing our model lacked is robust information on the internal characteristics of the homes we were analyzing. We knew very little about the improvements made to homes over time (or before listing) that would have a large impact of their selling price when put on the market. Even more information about who was selling them â€“ long-term owners, banks, or LLCs â€“ would have informed our model in interesting ways. From this, we could garner more information about the physical investment in both the individual homes and the neighborhoods they are in to better inform our model.
